New Rules for the Global Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let's assume that the leading world politicians would once again gather in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new global economic order.
They would naturally focus first on today's problems: the crisis in the Eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, addressing these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of global economic arrangements.
Here are seven common-sense principles for global economic management that they might possibly agree on.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. Markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow through the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other social institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies just as much to global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, a democratic form of government will largely be organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may be somewhat weaker, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments will cede substantial control to transnational institutions; moreover, rule harmonization would be of no benefit to societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems more likely to confirm it.
We too often waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals. In the end, weak results emerge that represent the smallest common denominator among the major countries.
If international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the WTO rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes in our own country, rather than destroying them.

3. Pluralistic prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives each country the freedom to develop institutions that best suit its needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have generated comparable prosperity in the long run.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security systems, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – one for each decade – is then presented as the great success to which one should aspire.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experimentation and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A global economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will tend to foster rather than suppress such experimental openness and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may seem harmless.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing views of globalization supporters.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools available to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries can retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect the health and safety of consumers – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
If advocates of globalization are right, the call for such protective measures will fail due to lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – both receive appropriate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to preserve values and rules in their own country is not to be confused with the use of such restrictions to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Just as little should they allow the US or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure tactics to change labor market rules, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.

6. International economic agreements to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on the nation-states to provide the basic regulatory functions of the global economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system had clear rules, although they were limited in scope and depth.
A complete catch-as-catch-can would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the global economy, which help vehicles of different size, shape, and speed to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive for a maximum of globalization that is in harmony with preserving space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot claim the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Therefore, different, less liberal rules must apply to undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
